# Coding Standards

## General (all languages)

- Explicit over implicit — if it's not obvious, name it clearly
- No dead code committed — remove before pushing, not "maybe later"
- Every public API (function, endpoint, component) gets a comment explaining *why* it exists, not what it does
- Environment-specific values go in `.env` files, never hardcoded
- Commit convention: **Conventional Commits** (see Git Workflow below)

## Naming Conventions

| Concept | Convention |
|---|---|
| Files (TS/TSX) | `kebab-case.ts` |
| Files (C++) | `snake_case.cpp / .h` |
| React components | `PascalCase` |
| C++ classes | `PascalCase` |
| C++ functions | `snake_case` |
| Environment vars | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` |
| API routes | `/api/v1/resource/:id` — versioned from day one |

## Error Handling

- Never swallow errors silently
- C++: use return codes + structured error types, not raw exceptions for control flow
- TypeScript: always `catch (e)` with a log and a typed re-throw or user-facing message
- HTTP errors must return a consistent JSON shape: `{ "error": "message", "code": "ERROR_CODE" }`

## Git Workflow

### Branches
```
main                          ← protected, always deployable, never commit directly
feat/TASK-NNN-description     ← new features
fix/TASK-NNN-description      ← bug fixes
infra/description             ← Docker, Nginx, CI changes
docs/description              ← ADRs, system design, README only
```

One task = one branch = one PR. No exceptions.

### Commit Convention (Conventional Commits)
```
feat(scope): description       ← new capability
fix(scope): description        ← bug fix
test(scope): description       ← adding/updating tests
infra(scope): description      ← infrastructure change
docs(scope): description       ← documentation only
refactor(scope): description   ← no behavior change
chore(scope): description      ← build, tooling
wip(scope): description        ← work in progress, not final
```

**Scope** = service or area: `core-api`, `uploader-api`, `watcher-api`, `streawman-ui`, `docker`, `nginx`, `ci`, `adr`

Examples:
- `feat(core-api): add JWT validation middleware`
- `fix(uploader-api): handle missing file in transcoder`
- `wip(core-api): auth handler skeleton — not ready`

### PR Rules
- `wip:` commits allowed freely during development — must be replaced or squashed before PR opens
- PR title follows the same conventional commit format as commits
- Before opening a PR on GitHub, run "review task" in Cursor chat — AI checks every acceptance criterion and returns READY / NOT READY
- PRs merge to `main` only after all acceptance criteria are checked off in `docs/tasks/current.md` and the review verdict is READY
